<DOC><DOCNO> AP890618-0016 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-18-89 1140EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Glance     06-18 0256</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Greece-Glance,0276</SECOND><HEAD>Greek Election at a Glance</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Greece, Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Here are some facts and figures on the Greek national electionSunday.</TEXT><TEXT>   POLITICAL PARTIES _ There are 25 political parties disputing thenational elections.   The largest party is Premier Andreas Papandreou's PanhellenicSocialist Movement (PASOK). PASOK was founded in 1974.   Constantine Mitsotakis' center-right New Democracy Party, alsofounded in 1974, is Greece's second-largest party.   The third-largest party is the Coalition of the Left andProgress, a political grouping made up of the Moscow-line GreekCommunist Party, the Eurocommunist Greek Left and socialistdissidents. The coalition was founded this year.</TEXT><TEXT>   PREVIOUS GOVERNMENT TERMS _ PASOK was elected in 1981 and againin 1985. New Democracy ruled between 1974 and 1981.</TEXT><TEXT>   1985 ELECTION RESULTS:   PASOK won 45.82 percent of the vote and 161 seats.   New Democracy won 40.84 percent and 126 seats.   The Greek Communist Party won 9.89 percent and 12 seats.   The Greek Left (Eurocommunist) won 1.84 percent and one seat.</TEXT><TEXT>   PARLIAMENT _ The Greek parliament is a 300-seat, one-chamberbody. In June, 1989 PASOK had 154 seats, New Democracy had 111, theGreek Communist Party 9, Democratic Renewal _ a conservativesplinter group _ 8, the Greek Left had 1 and independents had 17seats.</TEXT><TEXT>   THE PEOPLE _ There are approximately 10 million Greeks. Of the7,892,904 registered voters, 4,033,550 are women and 3,859,354 aremen.</TEXT><TEXT>   POLLING STATIONS _ There are 20,081 voting stations nationwide.They open at 6:00 a.m. and close at 9:00 p.m.</TEXT></DOC>